            <div type="note" subtype="biographical">
                <head type="title"><persName corresp="#MONROROBERTMRS">Mrs. Monro</persName></head>
                <p><persName corresp="#MONROROBERTMRS">Mrs. Monro</persName>, whom <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> addresses in the letter copied in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, may have been the mother of <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary Monro</persName>, 
                    the &#x201c;extremely good and beautiful Scotch girl&#x201d; who married <persName corresp="#RG">Richard Gray</persName>, as described in <title type="book" corresp="#JRPRAETERITA"><hi rend="italic">Praeterita</hi></title> 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 35:100). <persName corresp="#RG">Gray</persName> was a Scotsman who pursued a career much like that 
                    of <persName corresp="#JJR">John James Ruskin</persName>. In <date when="1812">1812</date>, when <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> was growing frustrated with his position in the wine firm 
                    of <orgName corresp="#GORDONMURPHYCO">Gordon, Murphy &#x0026; Company</orgName>, he remarked that &#x201c;<persName corresp="#RG">Gray</persName> is doing a great deal at <placeName corresp="#LISBON">Lisbon</placeName> &#x0026; is a Merchant of consequence 
                    now . . . I look upon his fortune as made&#x201d; (<title type="letter" corresp="#jjr_to_cr_1812-10-05">John James to Catherine Ruskin, 5 October 1812</title>, in 
                    <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.html#RFL">Burd, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 1:58). 
                    In <title type="book" corresp="#JRPRAETERITA"><hi rend="italic">Praeterita</hi></title>, <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> also characterizes <persName corresp="#RG">Richard</persName> as resembling his father 
                    in the &#x201c;scholarly love of good literature&#x201d;, and even exceeding him in &#x201c;romantic sentiment&#x201d;. 
                    <persName corresp="#RG">Gray</persName> probably helped <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> navigate foreign life in <placeName corresp="#SPAIN">Spain</placeName> and <placeName corresp="#PORTUGAL">Portugal</placeName>, when <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> traveled there sometime between <date notBefore="1815" notAfter="1817">1815 and 1817</date> 
                    to learn about sherry production (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 35:100; 
                    <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#SCOTTISHHERITAGE"><persName corresp="#HGV">Viljoen</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#SCOTTISHHERITAGE"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin&#x02bc;s Scottish Heritage</hi></title></ref>, 238&#x2013;39 n. 14). It was during <persName corresp="#RG">Gray</persName>&#x02bc;s time in <placeName corresp="#LISBON">Lisbon</placeName>, according to <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, 
                    that he met and married <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary Monro</persName>.</p>
                
                <p>Later, in <date when="1823">1823</date>, when <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> was becoming securely positioned with his own firm, <orgName corresp="#RUSKINETAL">Ruskin, Telford, &#x0026; Domecq</orgName>, 
                    he moved his family to a house atop <placeName type="building" corresp="#HERNE">Herne Hill</placeName> in the <placeName corresp="#LONDON">London</placeName> suburb of <placeName corresp="#CAMBERWELL">Camberwell</placeName>, where 
                    <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary</persName> and <persName corresp="#RG">Richard Gray</persName> were either already established or would soon become near neighbors. 
                    (<persName corresp="#JSD">Dearden</persName> suggests that the Grays arrived at 2 Grove Hill Terrace<!--unsure if this refers to a block of builings on Grove Hill Rd, or if Grove Hill Terrace was its own street during this time. MJF--> in <placeName corresp="#CAMBERWELL">Camberwell</placeName> after the Ruskins had settled in <placeName type="building" corresp="#HERNE">Herne Hill</placeName>; 
                    however, a <title type="letter" corresp="#mr_to_jjr_1822-01-30">letter</title> by <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret</persName> to <persName corresp="#JJR">John James Ruskin</persName> of <date when="1822-01-30">30 January 1822</date> indicates that the Grays were then living in <placeName corresp="#CAMBERWELL">Camberwell</placeName>, 
                    where <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret</persName> took <persName corresp="#JR">John</persName> for an extended stay [<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#DEARDENRUSKINSCAMBERWELL"><title type="book" corresp="#DEARDENRUSKINSCAMBERWELL"><hi rend="italic">John Ruskin's Camberwell</hi></title></ref>, 23; <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 107).
                    Living with the Grays was <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary</persName>&#x02bc;s mother, &#x201c;old Mrs. Monro&#x201d; and her &#x201c;white French poodle, Petite&#x201d; 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE"><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE"><hi rend="italic">Works</hi></title></ref>, 35:101). Even prior to the <placeName corresp="#CAMBERWELL">Camberwell</placeName> residence at <placeName type="building" corresp="#HERNE">Herne Hill</placeName>, however, &#x201c;Mrs. Gray &#x0026; Mrs. Monro&#x201d; 
                    were apparently regular visitors to the Ruskins&#x02bc; <placeName type="building" corresp="#HUNTERST">Hunter Street</placeName> house in <placeName corresp="#LONDON">London</placeName>. In <date when="1821">1821</date>, for example, 
                    <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret</persName> wrote to <persName corresp="#JJR">John James</persName> describing a visit by <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary</persName> and her mother during which <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary</persName> sat with <persName corresp="#JR">John</persName> 
                    &#x201c;on the drawing room floor very deeply engrossed&#x201d; in teaching <persName corresp="#JR">John</persName> to play the flute. 
                    Since the Gray household proved childless, the Grays and <persName corresp="#MONROROBERTMRS">Mrs. Monro</persName> continued to take great interest in <persName corresp="#JR">John</persName>&#x02bc;s development 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 59&#x2013;60 n. 8, 100&#x2013;101).</p>
                
                <p>While <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary</persName>&#x02bc;s mother seems the likeliest addresse of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02bc;s letter copied in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, 
                    another possible <persName corresp="#MONROROBERTMRS">Mrs. Monro</persName> may have been the wife of <persName corresp="#RMONRO">Robert Monro</persName>, a brother of <persName corresp="#MMONRO">Mary</persName>. 
                    The maiden name of this <persName corresp="#MONROROBERTMRS">Mrs. Monro</persName> was Dowie. All three families&#x2014;the Grays, the Monros, and the Dowies&#x2014;were 
                    lifelong friends of the Ruskins
                    (see <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#RFL"><persName corresp="#VAB">Burd</persName>, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#RFL"><hi rend="italic">Ruskin Family Letters</hi></title></ref>, 1:100. 101 n. 5, 121, 123 n. 4).</p>
               
            </div>
